Caveat

  • During the data cleaning and visualization, we found that the data from October is missing. The reason is the IATA_CODE in this month has the format of 5 digit code while others have only three letter. So we did some search online and use the code below to solve this issue. Namely, change all the 5 digit code to 3 letters. (CITE: https://www.kaggle.com/smiller933/fixing-airport-codes/code)
Airport_ID_to_IATA <- function (x) {
  df <- data.frame (ID = as.character (x), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  num_records = nrow (df)
  dfAirportID <- read.csv ("https://www.transtats.bts.gov/Download_Lookup.asp?Lookup=L_AIRPORT_ID",
                           colClasses=c("character", "character"), 
                           col.names=c("AirportID", "Description"))
  df <- dplyr::left_join (df, dfAirportID, by=c("ID" = "AirportID"))
  dfAirport <- read.csv ("https://www.transtats.bts.gov/Download_Lookup.asp?Lookup=L_AIRPORT",
                         colClasses=c("character", "character"), 
                         col.names=c("IATA_CODE", "Description"))
  dfAirport <- dfAirport [! (dfAirport$IATA_CODE %in% c('BSM', 'NYL')),]
  dfAirport = dfAirport[-which(duplicated(dfAirport$Description)),]
  df <- dplyr::left_join (df, dfAirport, by="Description")
  df$ID <- dplyr::coalesce (df$IATA_CODE, df$ID)
  return (df$ID)
}
data$ORIGIN_AIRPORT <- Airport_ID_to_IATA (data$ORIGIN_AIRPORT)
data$DESTINATION_AIRPORT <- Airport_ID_to_IATA (data$DESTINATION_AIRPORT)

Delay Visualization

  • A little dig into the data, we found that AIR_SYSTEM_DELAY + SECURITY_DELAY + AIRLINE_DELAY + LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY + WEATHER_DELAY = ARRIVAL_DELAY.
  • AIR_SYSTEM_DELAY, SECURITY_DELAY, AIRLINE_DELAY, LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY, WEATHER_DELAY have many NAs. Why? It turns out that when the ARRIVAL_DEALY is less than 10, NAs will appear in these columns. We will replace NAs with 0 to indicate that the delay is not caused by any of the reasons above, and replace other values with 1 to indicate that delay was caused by one or more of the 5 reasons. (This potentially solves the dependent columns)
subdata[which(is.na(subdata$AIRLINE_DELAY) == TRUE), c(27:31)] = 0
subdata[which(subdata$AIR_SYSTEM_DELAY != 0), 27] = 1
subdata[which(subdata$SECURITY_DELAY != 0), 28] = 1
subdata[which(subdata$AIRLINE_DELAY != 0), 29] = 1
subdata[which(subdata$LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY != 0), 30] = 1
subdata[which(subdata$WEATHER_DELAY != 0), 31] = 1
  • How many flights are delayed? What are their proportions?
flights.delay = subdata$ARRIVAL_DELAY
flights.delay[flights.delay > 0] = 'Delayed'
flights.delay[flights.delay <= 0] = "Not Delayed"
ggplot(data=as.data.frame(flights.delay), aes(flights.delay, fill = flights.delay)) + geom_bar(stat="count", width=0.5) + scale_fill_manual("legend", values = c("Delayed" = "orange", "Not Delayed" = "blue")) + geom_text(stat='count', aes(label=..count..), vjust=-0.5) + labs(x = "Delay / Not Delay", y = "Count", color = flights.delay)

  • In our dataset, there are less delayed flights than on time filghts, which means some sampling methods will be used to deal with the dataset.

  • To make it more interesting, let’s categorize the delay time into four categories:
    • Level 0: Not Delayed or somewhat delayed
    • Level 1: Slightly Delayed (less than 30 minutes)
    • Level 2: Moderately Delayed (larger than 30 minutes and less than am hour)
    • Level 3: Seriously Delayed (larger than an hour)

  • Visualize the distribution of our categories

subdata$ARRIVAL_DELAY_LEVEL = delay.level
ggplot(data=as.data.frame(subdata$ARRIVAL_DELAY_LEVEL), aes(subdata$ARRIVAL_DELAY_LEVEL, fill = subdata$ARRIVAL_DELAY_LEVEL)) + geom_bar(width=0.5) + scale_fill_manual("Delay Level", values = c("0" = "green", '1' = "blue", '2' = "orange", '3' = "red")) + geom_text(stat='count', aes(label=..count..), vjust=-0.5) + labs(x = "Delay Level", y = "Count", color = "Delay Level")

Handling regression and classification data

  • Closer scrutiny of our dataset and even without looking at the data, we firmly believe that the arrival delay is correlated with the departure delay. This may cause difficulty or may place us in unfair advantage if we keep this feature.
ggplot(data.frame(balanced.data$ARRIVAL_DELAY, balanced.data$DEPARTURE_DELAY), aes(x =balanced.data.ARRIVAL_DELAY, y = balanced.data.DEPARTURE_DELAY)) + geom_point() + labs(x = 'Arrival Delay', y = 'Departure Delay')

  • The plot confirms our intuition. We will remove departure delay for fairness!
balanced.data = balanced.data[, -12]

Split train and test set (80% and 20%)

  • Entries in column CANCELLED, DIVERTED and YEAR are the same in this dataset so we remove as it will not provide any information to the model.
  • CANCELLATION_REASON has no entries.
  • Entries in column ARRIVAL_TIME can provide direct information on ARRIVAL_DELAY, as ARRIVAL_DELAY = ARRIVAL_TIME - SCHEDULED_ARRIVAL_TIME. If we keep this feature than there is no need to deal with the models so we drop this one.
balanced.data = balanced.data[, -c(which(colnames(balanced.data) == 'DIVERTED'),
                                   which(colnames(balanced.data) == 'CANCELLED'),
                                   which(colnames(balanced.data) == 'CANCELLATION_REASON'),
                                   which(colnames(balanced.data) == 'YEAR'),
                                   which(colnames(balanced.data) == 'ARRIVAL_TIME'))]
write.csv(balanced.data, file = "BalanceData.csv",row.names=FALSE)
train.idx = sample(nrow(balanced.data), nrow(balanced.data) * 0.8)
train.data = balanced.data[train.idx,]
test.data = balanced.data[-train.idx,]
train.data = change_to_numeric(train.data)
test.data = change_to_numeric(test.data)

  • We have 130215 rows of training data and 32554 rows of testing data.

train.data.reg = data.frame(train.data[, -which(colnames(train.data) == 'ARRIVAL_DELAY_LEVEL')])
test.data.reg = data.frame(test.data[, -which(colnames(test.data) == 'ARRIVAL_DELAY_LEVEL')])
  • Data for classification:
train.data.clf = data.frame(train.data[, -which(colnames(train.data) == 'ARRIVAL_DELAY')])
test.data.clf = data.frame(test.data[, -which(colnames(test.data) == 'ARRIVAL_DELAY')])

PCA (Just for visualization, only use regression data)

library(ggfortify)
df = data.frame(train.data.clf[, -ncol(train.data.clf)])
data.pc = prcomp(df)
vars = apply(data.pc$x, 2, var)  
props = vars / sum(vars)
props = data.frame(cbind(1:(ncol(train.data.clf)-1), cumsum(props)))
colnames(props) = c('PCA', 'Cumulative.Variance')
ggplot(props, aes(x=PCA, y=Cumulative.Variance)) + geom_point(color='blue') + geom_line(color='red')

  • We see that the first 9 principle components explained almost all the variance in the dataset. This once again certified our variance selection using random forest.

  • We plot the first 4 principle components due to the limited computing resoursce

pairs(data.pc$x[,1:9], col=c("red", "blue", "orange", "green")[as.factor(train.data.clf[,ncol(train.data.clf)])], pch = 19)

test.data.clf = test.data.clf[, c(select.idx.clf, ncol(test.data.clf))]

write.csv(train.data.clf, file = "TrainData_clf.csv",row.names=FALSE)
write.csv(test.data.clf, file = "TestData_clf.csv",row.names=FALSE)
  • Our cleaned data for classifcation:
    • training data: 130215 rows, 10 columns (including response variable)
    • test data: 32554 rows, 10 columns (including response variable)
